<h3><a name="association">What is the association between <i>Labels, Artists, Albums</i> and <i>Tracks</i>?</a></h3>
<p>
	Well, things are sophisticated in the music business. As it would be rather confusing than pleasuring 
	to model each and every possible association computer-beatz focus on the following:<br />
	No association is a must, so no item has to be associated with some other!
	<ul>
		<li>
			A <i>Track</i> (or Song) is created by an <i>Artist</i> (also see <a href="#colab">Collaborations</a>) 
			and thus can be associated with one (exactly one). An <i>Artist</i> may have many <i>Tracks</i>.
		</li>
		<li>
			A <i>Track</i> also can be associated with an <i>Album</i>. As a track might be published 
			on a <a href="#compilations">Compilation</a> as well, tracks can be associated with 
			several albums. An <i>Album</i> has many <i>Tracks</i>.
		</li>
		<li>
			A <i>Track</i> can be associated with a <i>Label</i>. A <i>Label</i> has many <i>Tracks</i> 
			in turn.
		</li>
		<li>
			An <i>Album</i> can be associated with exactly <b>one</b> <i>Artist</i> (also see 
			<a href="#compilations">Compilations</a>). An <i>Artist</i> can have many <i>Albums</i>.
		<li>
			An <i>Album</i> can be associated with exactly <b>one</b> <i>Label</i> (also see 
			<a href="#compilations">Compilations</a>). <i>Labels</i> have many <i>Albums</i> in turn.
		</li>
		<li>
			Because of the associations between <i>Tracks</i> / <i>Albums</i> and <i>Labels</i> on the 
			one hand and the association between <i>Tracks</i> and <i>Artists</i> on the other, 
			<i>Artists</i> are associated indirectly with possibly many Labels.
		</li>
	</ul>
</p>
