<h3><a name="colab">How are collaborations of artists modelled in the database?</a></h3>
<p>
	As mentioned before - things are sophisticated! Computer-beatz does it like that:<br />
	<i>Artist 1</i> and <i>Artist 2</i> both might have publications on their own. And those two might 
	have publications together, like <i>Artist 1 vs. Artist 2</i>. We do not model this kind of association. 
	So the collaboration is considered to be an extra artist. This keeps things a little easier and you will 
	still find such collaborations if you e.g. search for <i>Artist 1</i>. 
</p>
<a href="#top">Back to index</a>
<h3><a name="compilations">How are compilations are modelled in the database?</a></h3>
<p>
	Gotta repeat, that things are sophisticated. 
	A compilation is an <i>Album</i> with some specialities. It features many artists. 
	Because of that, a compilation (an <i>Album</i>), should 
	<b>not</b> be associated with an <i>Artist</i> - that`s nonsens! As having many <i>Tracks</i>, the compilation is indirectly 
	associated with many artists. Well, this association is currently not shown, but you will find the artists 
	when you click one of the compilation`s tracks.
</p>
